WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:23.240
Listen carefully. What you will hear now is the voice of a 14-year-old boy who already

00:23.240 --> 00:53.000
has tasted more violence than most people do in a lifetime.

00:53.000 --> 00:58.440
The boy is talking about his father. The man facing you can listen to this sort of thing

00:58.440 --> 01:04.040
without burning a hair. He's a counselor at a Los Angeles County Forestry Camp for

01:04.040 --> 01:10.440
boys who've gotten in trouble. Boys like this 14-year-old who talks almost casually of

01:10.440 --> 01:16.640
drunkenness and stabbing. You'll hear this kid's own story. You'll see how the forestry

01:16.640 --> 01:22.160
camp officials are trying to set him straight. And you'll visit San Quentin. For the story

01:22.160 --> 01:29.580
of this man, Carol Chessman, who began as a juvenile offender and ended up on Death

01:29.580 --> 01:45.200
Road. All this on program 2 of Focus on Delinquency. A special report from the KNXT Department

01:45.200 --> 01:56.240
of Public Affairs. The story begins at Juvenile Hall. Last week, you saw how the hall works.

01:56.240 --> 02:00.680
But to get the flavor of the place, you have to talk with the kids as I did on a bench

02:00.680 --> 02:27.920
beside the football field.

02:27.920 --> 02:36.440
Your folks know your drink? Yes, sir. Don't they mine? Well, I live with my stepdad and

02:36.440 --> 02:45.120
my mom. I don't like stepping and he doesn't like me. Well, what sort of trouble is it,

02:45.120 --> 02:52.240
is it? Oh, the whole trouble. Mostly home trouble. Yeah, your family. It's pretty messed up.

02:52.240 --> 02:56.560
How come? I was probably my fault and then the end of the end of the fall.

02:56.560 --> 03:03.200
Mother and father divorced, didn't they? How long you in court? Well, I went to

03:03.200 --> 03:08.600
queer studenters and set up a camp program for me. How long are you going to be there? Well,

03:08.600 --> 03:14.640
approximately from six, six months to nine. Going back to school and you get out? Yes, sir.

03:14.640 --> 03:20.280
What do you think you'll do when you get out of school? How many ideas? Well, I'll try

03:20.280 --> 03:26.760
not to get any more trouble for one thing. You got a girlfriend outside? Yes, I do a lot of

03:26.760 --> 03:32.040
thinking about her myself, you know. What does she think about all this, you know? Well, I don't know.

03:32.040 --> 03:38.240
She's also ashamed of me. Because she's mostly she, you know, I always tell her what

03:38.240 --> 03:44.480
happened. So, you know, usually when I got in trouble, I'll tell her and then she told me to

03:44.480 --> 03:50.600
go out of my wife's up and go straight, you know. And I told her, yes, I would. I'd just turn

03:50.600 --> 03:56.760
around and, you know, do the worst again. What do you think ought to be done about it to prevent

03:56.760 --> 04:04.000
that sort of trouble? Well, they say there were more things for the kids to do. It would keep

04:04.000 --> 04:13.760
them out of trouble. What do I think they get in here for? Well, it's not. On the mid-lust

04:13.760 --> 04:19.360
times, there's an air fall because sometimes they lose up. You know, see, like they say,

04:19.360 --> 04:23.200
their father and mother don't pay much attention to them. They don't get all the love they're

04:23.200 --> 04:30.040
supposed to get in. Last week, we picked up the composite case of a young

04:30.040 --> 04:36.200
car thief named Eddie Smith. The names and facts are scrambled because California law for

04:36.200 --> 04:41.800
bids identification of juveniles in matters like these. But there are no actors in this

04:41.800 --> 04:47.560
story. The people and the problems are real. And Eddie's problem is especially real for him,

04:47.560 --> 04:53.440
as he returns to court to hear the verdict of Judge William B. McCus. The boy has spent two

04:53.440 --> 04:58.960
weeks in juvenile hall while the authorities investigated his home, his family, and his trouble

04:58.960 --> 05:05.120
with the law. The probation report recommends that Eddie be sent to a county forestry camp. As he

05:05.120 --> 05:10.620
usually does, Judge McCus and follows that recommendation and he makes it an order.

05:10.620 --> 05:22.360
Eddie does go to a forestry camp, away from the neighborhood and friends and environment

05:22.360 --> 05:27.760
that up to now have worked against him. And incidentally, away from the parents who tried

05:27.760 --> 05:33.920
to make things work, but just didn't try hard enough or didn't know. So now, in the case

05:33.920 --> 05:39.640
of Eddie Smith, the law takes over. But let's listen, as the case of Eddie in juvenile court

05:39.640 --> 05:45.800
comes to a conclusion. Stand on your own feet and understand that your conduct

05:45.800 --> 05:51.040
had to be different in order to stay out of trouble. You may have just gone along because

05:51.040 --> 05:57.760
the rest of the guys did it. I think that you would benefit from the opportunity our forestry

05:57.760 --> 06:02.840
camp program, which we have available here for boys in Los Angeles County. We have five

06:02.840 --> 06:08.400
since camps, Mr. Smith. Two of them are what we call our school cast because they're for

06:08.400 --> 06:13.800
boys under 16 where they have full-time day school. The other three are for the boys over

06:13.800 --> 06:19.000
16 where the boys work eight hours a day for the county forestry and fire warden building

06:19.000 --> 06:22.560
fire trails and fighting forest fires and work of that kind.

06:22.560 --> 06:30.560
Now, Eddie, you are under 16 and you're therefore under the compulsory school age in this

06:30.560 --> 06:35.560
state and will be placed in a school camp or you'll go to regular day school. You'll

06:35.560 --> 06:40.640
get credit for this work when you come back into your own school. We don't send the boys

06:40.640 --> 06:46.040
to camp for a fixed length of time, Eddie. Depends on you. Kind of a record you make for

06:46.040 --> 06:51.920
yourself. Our program, of course, divided in the various stages and as you progress through

06:51.920 --> 06:58.800
the various stages, you may do it rapidly and it may take longer. But the kind of record

06:58.800 --> 07:05.400
you make is up to you. You're not sentenced to fixed length of time. That's what I want

07:05.400 --> 07:12.960
to impress upon you and therefore the opportunity is yours by making a good record to shorten

07:12.960 --> 07:19.280
your stay or by making a bad record that it's necessary for you to stay longer.

07:19.280 --> 07:25.000
It's official now. Eddie is legally a ward of the juvenile court of Los Angeles County.

07:25.000 --> 07:29.960
But the important thing to the boy is that he's leaving juvenile hall. No more steel

07:29.960 --> 07:36.120
screens on the windows. No more walls and gates and doors locked against escape. Judge

07:36.120 --> 07:48.520
McKesson has, in effect, decided that Eddie needs a fresh start in fresh new surroundings.

07:48.520 --> 07:54.200
This is one of five forestry camps operated by the county. Back in a secluded canyon,

07:54.200 --> 07:59.200
it's still close enough to get an occasional heavy dose of Los Angeles smog. But even

07:59.200 --> 08:04.840
so, for many of these boys, it's the cleanest air they've ever breathed. The newcomers

08:04.840 --> 08:10.160
are met by a staff member who takes their old clothes. They get a complete outfitting,

08:10.160 --> 08:17.480
denims and work shoes. No fancy teenage styles, but it's just right for outdoor living.

08:17.480 --> 08:22.840
If he never did before, a boy learns to take care of his own clothes. Then the old hands

08:22.840 --> 08:29.680
take the new ones to the dormitory. It's spotlessly clean. The boys do their own housework.

08:29.680 --> 08:39.120
Each has something precious, a rosary, a picture, a guitar, the flag, a crucifix, or an award

08:39.120 --> 08:49.560
perhaps for sports or citizenship. There is full-time schooling here. Many boys who never

08:49.560 --> 08:55.160
took to it before suddenly learn to read and write for the first time. True and C is an

08:55.160 --> 09:01.520
early symptom for many delinquents, and of course, there's none of that here. But it's

09:01.520 --> 09:08.200
not all work and no play. The camp setting is Southern California at its best, beautiful

09:08.200 --> 09:15.840
wooded mountains. The program includes swimming as a reward for good work and good behavior.

09:15.840 --> 09:26.720
It looks like the old swimming hall of a gentler time, and it certainly is invited.

09:26.720 --> 09:32.640
The boys earn their fun. It's their camp. It's up to them to keep it in shape. Responsibility

09:32.640 --> 09:38.080
is a good teacher, and every boy has certain duties he must perform. And you might guess

09:38.080 --> 09:44.000
that in this age group, kitchen duty is the most popular of all. Hungry boys surrounded

09:44.000 --> 09:51.120
by food. The self-reliance idea is carried out in craft classes like woodshop. A boy learns

09:51.120 --> 09:56.080
enough to help him get a job when he leaves, and in the mean time he makes things for himself

09:56.080 --> 10:02.440
and for the camp. The dining hall groups have taken the names of Indian tribes. The signs

10:02.440 --> 10:17.720
are made by the boys themselves. A pointed reminder goes straight. And another reminder of

10:17.720 --> 10:26.920
the right way to live. Not a fence or wall or gate anywhere, and after touring the camp,

10:26.920 --> 10:32.360
I talked with the director, Mr. Eugene Cox, a career man in the probation department.

10:32.360 --> 10:39.800
The boys who run away, why do you think they do it? Several boys that run away, in fact,

10:39.800 --> 10:45.160
quite a percentage, run away simply because they don't have enough stability to face this

10:45.160 --> 10:52.760
type of a challenge in a way. They are able to run away, and they know that we do not

10:52.760 --> 11:00.520
chase them, and since they are somewhat lacking in making good choices, some boys are run away simply

11:00.520 --> 11:06.520
because they can't help it. Other boys will run away because the liberty and the freedom here

11:06.520 --> 11:12.280
is simply too threatening for them and they can't face it. So they will use the usual routine

11:12.280 --> 11:18.120
of running away. The challenge is to speak up, by assuming the very freedom of the camp itself.

11:18.520 --> 11:24.440
Yes, and we try to use that as effectively as possible, given that each boy is much responsibility,

11:24.440 --> 11:30.120
as we think he is able to handle within the program. This, of course, is the responsibility

11:30.120 --> 11:34.680
degree is very slight with new boys and increases gradually as the boy becomes older.

11:34.680 --> 11:38.920
So what are you trying to do with them? By giving them an all-responsibility.

11:38.920 --> 11:45.320
We realize that most boys return to the same community that they leave, and we know that if we,

11:45.320 --> 11:52.520
in some way, can't alter them and improve their basic abilities, the handle of social situations,

11:52.520 --> 11:58.520
that they will become a domain claim again. So by giving them as much responsibility,

11:58.520 --> 12:06.360
social acceptance, and maturity, and equal strength as we can, then we are doing what we know how to do

12:06.360 --> 12:10.520
to enable them to have a better opportunity to behave when they return home.

12:11.480 --> 12:17.880
Cox refers to his camp as around the clock treatment center, not punishment, but treatment.

12:17.880 --> 12:23.720
Perhaps the most important part is the counseling, getting the boy to talk about his home and his

12:23.720 --> 12:31.640
trouble and himself. Again and again, the boys tell of broken homes, the same story with 100 variations.

12:32.280 --> 12:38.280
Judge McKesson tells us that two-thirds of all the boys he sees in court have broken homes behind

12:38.280 --> 12:45.720
them, broken by divorce, desertion, or cold indifference. The staff members who do the counseling

12:45.720 --> 12:52.200
are specially trained, highly skilled at drawing out the youngsters. The boys are looked on not as

12:52.200 --> 12:58.520
prisoners, but patients. The counselor is not a policeman, but more a father-confesser with

12:58.520 --> 13:04.600
training in psychology. It's the counselor's job to understand the boy and help him understand

13:04.840 --> 13:11.160
himself. To get him to talk out his troubles, instead of acting them out, in deeds of violence.

13:11.160 --> 13:17.320
You looked in on this counseling session a few minutes ago. The boy is 14 years old, intelligent,

13:17.320 --> 13:23.240
and good looking. Remember, we had to cut names and places to protect the boy's identity.

13:23.240 --> 13:25.880
This is his story in his own words.

13:25.880 --> 13:30.600
Finally school started and I started it off. School started your problems?

13:30.600 --> 13:35.320
