Something to bother somebody. Yeah, felt the need to bother someone. Well, we couldn't just settle down,

16:29.240 --> 16:33.960
we couldn't stay still. We always had to be doing something. Kind of restless, nervous.

16:33.960 --> 16:36.680
I said, no, he's got to be on a move. He can't stay in one spot tomorrow.

16:37.640 --> 16:41.160
Well, like, you know, when I was a girl at that one, we went to a dance church, you know,

16:41.160 --> 16:45.560
church, you know, a little deals, you know? So we went up there enough. So I got home about five

16:45.560 --> 16:50.040
after ten. I started writing out this voluntary report of mine. To the police. Yes,

16:50.040 --> 16:53.160
for the old man, it's mad about it, you know? He said, let me read it. I said, there was

16:53.160 --> 16:56.840
none of his business. So he said, what'd you say? And I said, you heard me and he hit me in the back

16:56.840 --> 17:01.400
in the neck. I got mad about, and I jumped up and I told him, all right, you want to do it that way,

17:01.400 --> 17:05.880
let's get out with it. I hit him. So when I need to pull out his belt, he started to hit me with a

17:05.880 --> 17:10.680
bug buckle and I got mad about it. I told him, let me, like a man, like a coward. He wouldn't. So

17:10.680 --> 17:14.760
he turned around the walk away and I jumped him. And I had him in the corner where I was kicking him

17:14.760 --> 17:18.600
with a punch and I did everything. Finally, he just landed what good when that was it. I was out.

17:19.240 --> 17:22.120
So finally, call the cops about a little bit like he woke me up, you know?

17:23.400 --> 17:28.120
I fell asleep and went, everything. Just, you know how it is? Just see how I saw him.

17:28.120 --> 17:31.800
I brought you the juvenile hall and that's where he placed you.

17:32.760 --> 17:37.960
You learn a lot from these kids, like the difference between slicing and stabbing.

17:39.000 --> 17:43.880
That boy was a newcomer to camp in there only a couple of weeks, but already he's talking

17:43.880 --> 17:50.120
easily, working hard in school, and for the first time in his life, he's found a place. He's

17:50.120 --> 17:55.800
fitting in. The counselors think it's a good bet he'll make the grade. Now we'll listen in on

17:55.800 --> 18:01.240
another boy who's been around longer. He's stopped talking about the violence and hatred that got him

18:01.240 --> 18:07.800
in trouble. He's beginning to understand himself and his home, though for these boys, home is a

18:07.800 --> 18:16.680
word that has strange meanings. Before I got in trouble, I used to go home and I used to sit there,

18:16.680 --> 18:22.760
and I want to tell my mother, things would happen, you know? But I used to sit down there, she just

18:22.760 --> 18:29.480
used to look at me and tell me, well, you don't want to talk to me. You just, you know, you just want

18:29.480 --> 18:36.040
to be funny, you know? And I never got to ever say anything to my mother. I really wanted to get

18:36.040 --> 18:42.280
down to her. I used to call her mother because, well, I just heard that. You know, I mean, she was my

18:42.280 --> 18:46.440
mother. That's the only reason. I mean, I didn't have no feeling in storage as anybody, as I would

18:46.440 --> 18:52.200
anybody else. I mean, I don't know how she feel about me. She says she makes me and all that.

18:53.000 --> 19:01.160
She says I'm her son, but still, I mean, I never had much feeling, you know, and my home, I mean,

19:01.160 --> 19:06.360
I can't remember what my mother used to, you know, picking me up and putting her out from me and

19:06.360 --> 19:12.280
seeing I was her son because when they used to go out, then they never asked me if I wanted to go

19:12.280 --> 19:17.000
with them or anything. I mean, I mean, even if they did, probably I wouldn't want to do it anyway,

19:17.400 --> 19:23.080
you know? Because, I mean, every time I used to be home, I just wanted to get out of the house. I couldn't,

19:23.800 --> 19:28.600
I couldn't stand being there, you know? I didn't like to be home with them when they were in the house.

19:28.600 --> 19:35.160
I used to get up and walk by myself because my mother, well, I don't know, she just,

19:36.360 --> 19:40.600
I guess she wasn't used to it either, like I'm not used to it, you know? Yeah. But maybe that

19:40.600 --> 19:47.640
isn't the reason, but still, I mean, other people used to come to the house and she used to tell me,

19:47.640 --> 19:52.120
she used to how that meant everything when other people was there, you know? So, they were said,

19:52.120 --> 19:56.040
so then when people used to be there, you used to leave the house, you know?

19:56.760 --> 20:04.360
Oh, my father, I mean, I only see him, you know, a couple of times. I used to see him, I only

20:04.360 --> 20:11.560
called him a father because, well, you know, the people see you're fathering. I don't know, well,

20:11.560 --> 20:17.320
my father sees me, he acts nice to everything, but still, I mean, you can see them when he

20:17.320 --> 20:23.000
does, he's just trying to get back at my mother, you know? He's trying to get back at my mother

20:23.000 --> 20:28.280
through me, you know, not that he likes me or anything, they're each trying to, you know, fight, fight,

20:28.280 --> 20:33.080
fight, fight, they got me as a weapon, you know? The mother doesn't want me to see my father,

20:33.880 --> 20:38.920
my father wants me to come and do it, it's not because he likes me, but try and get back at each other,

20:38.920 --> 20:45.080
you know? So, have you in between now? Yeah, because I mean, I mean, I could be wrong, you know?

20:45.080 --> 20:51.080
But I mean, I think I should know more than anybody else, you know? But how much good does it do?

20:51.080 --> 20:58.040
How many of these boys leave camp? Never again to tangle with the law. The camp director, Mr. Cox,

20:58.040 --> 21:05.000
puts his success record between 70 and 80 percent. And at juvenile hall, when I asked the same

21:05.000 --> 21:10.520
question about success or failure, I got this answer from Mr. Clarence Cabell, the chief boys

21:10.520 --> 21:15.240
counselor. The talkers though a lot of them do make good, but how about those who don't? What

21:15.240 --> 21:22.520
happens to them? Well, unfortunately, we have occasion to go to the different institutions in

21:22.520 --> 21:29.560
the California and the honor farm and what I would consider the end of the live San Quentin,

21:30.680 --> 21:35.960
and the majority of the boys that end up in San Quentin have been boys that have repeated

21:35.960 --> 21:40.600
here so many times that we have told them that they're going to San Quentin if they didn't straighten

21:40.600 --> 21:47.080
up. And occasionally they walk up to you in institutions such as San Quentin and say, well,

21:47.080 --> 21:53.800
you told me so. So it's a pretty saddening thing to me to see them there, but although you have a

21:53.800 --> 22:00.840
feeling they're going to go years before it happens. There's one who made it in a hurry. Carol Chessman,

22:00.840 --> 22:07.320
the most notorious criminal since John Dillinger, the most publicized prison author of this century.

22:07.320 --> 22:15.080
And for his story, from his own lips, we went next to San Quentin. It's on a cold, windy arm of the

22:15.080 --> 22:22.520
Bay north of San Francisco. It's the biggest prison in California, 5,000 inmates. This is the

22:22.520 --> 22:27.880
big yard, every square inch of it under constant watch by the armed men on the gun walks.

22:31.080 --> 22:37.640
And this is death row, the small barred windows at the top of the North Salt Block.

22:37.640 --> 22:44.120
Chessman and 17 others are up there waiting to die. The size of the place is staggering,

22:44.120 --> 22:49.720
but it's not nearly big enough so they're doubling up two men to a cell. There are four blocks

22:49.720 --> 22:57.640
like this, hundreds of cells in each, five tiers high, a tremendous place with an odor that seems

22:57.640 --> 23:04.600
to linger on even after you leave. I toured the prison with the director of the State Department of

23:04.600 --> 23:14.040
Corrections, Richard McGee on the left and San Quentin's Warden Harley O'Teats. McGee and Warden

23:14.040 --> 23:21.480
Teats. They showed me Chessman's record. It's a long record, page after page of hand-lettered

23:21.480 --> 23:28.920
notations, dates, offenses, execution dates and delays. The record shows that Chessman once was a

23:28.920 --> 23:34.200
troublemaker in prison, fights with other cons and that sort of thing. But since he began writing

23:34.200 --> 23:39.240
nearly four years ago, he's had no trouble at all. He's fought only with the legal authorities

23:39.240 --> 23:51.320
